Antonia Marti, University of Barcelona Diana McCarthy, University of Sussex Vivi Nastase, University of Ottawa Hwee Tou Ng, National University of Singapore Martha Palmer, University of Pennsylvania Patrick Pantel, Information Sciences Institute Ted Pedersen, University of Minnesota, Duluth Judita Preiss, University of Cambridge Amruta Purandare, University of Minnesota Duluth German Rigau, University of the Basque Country Vasile Rus, Indiana University South-Bend Charles Schafer, Johns Hopkins University Carlo Strapparava, ITC-IRST Trento Dan Tufis, Romanian Academy Cynthia Thompson, University of Utah Paola Velardi, La Sapienza Rome Janyce Wiebe, University of Pittsburgh David Yarowsky, John Hopkins University Deniz Yuret, Koc University SPONSORS: European Language Resources Association (ELRA) National Science Foundation (NSF) ACL Special Interest Group on the Lexicon (SIGLEX) WEBSITE: http://www.senseval.org/senseval3 PREFACE This volume contains papers describing the tasks and participating systems in SENSEVAL-3  the Third International Workshop on the Evaluation of Systems for the Semantic Analysis of Text.
2:17	The SENSEVAL-3 workshop is held in conjunction with the Association for Computational Linguistics meeting on July 25-26, 2004 in Barcelona, Spain.
3:17	SENSEVAL-3 was very successful.
4:17	Fourteen different tasks were organized and 55 teams participated with over 160 systems.
5:17	Tasks included core word sense disambiguation tasks for various languages (Basque, Catalan, Chinese, English, Italian, Romanian, Spanish), and new tasks involving identification of semantic roles, logic forms, multilingual annotations, and subcategorization acquisition.
6:17	The papers represent a wide variety of state-of-the-art methods for word sense disambiguation and semantic analysis.
7:17	Although these proceedings include the descriptions of ALL tasks and systems participating in the evaluation, the papers are all peer-reviewed.
8:17	We were truly impressed by the high quality of the reviews provided by all the members of the program committee, particularly since deadlines were very tight.
9:17	The papers have benefited from that expert feedback.
10:17	When we first started planning this workshop, we agreed that having a high quality invited speaker was crucial.
11:17	We thank Kenneth Church not only for his talk, but also for the boost of confidence provided by his quick and enthusiastic acceptance.
12:17	We also thank the members of the two panels for providing discussion and insights on 1) applications for WSD and 2) planning Senseval-4.
13:17	The evaluation really comes down to the organization of the tasks.
14:17	The task organizers did a supreme job of task design, data creation, and administration, again on strong time constraints.
15:17	We are also grateful to the ACL 2004 conference organizers for local organization and the forum.
16:17	Finally, we most gratefully acknowledge the support of our sponsors, the European Language Resources Association (ELRA), the National Science Foundation (NSF), and the ACL Special Interest Group on the Lexicon (SIGLEX).
